A library can be considered a **system** because it consists of interconnected subsystems (e.g., cataloging, circulation, reference, and digital resources) that work together to achieve its purpose—providing access to information. While it may not fit the technical definition of a "system" in engineering or computing, it functions as an **organized whole** with interdependent parts. Options B, C, and D incorrectly dismiss its systemic nature.
